Fingers are pointed at the Nelson Mandela Bay municipality, as residents count down to Day Zero. Poor management and failing infrastructure are seen as the biggest reasons the metro's taps are running dry. Antony Martel, a member of the Water Crisis Committee and a PhD candidate in the Development Studies Department at Nelson Mandela University, co-authored a piece in the Daily Maverick on the looming Day Zero. He discussed the situation with eNCA's Shahan Ramkissoon. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - The Nelson Mandela Bay municipality is failing dismally to deal with the water crisis. This according to the Water Crisis Committee. READ:Â Slight decline in SA's water levels The metro is just days away from Day Zero. Antony Martel, a member of the Water Crisis Committee, said: "From an administrative standpoint which is an issue of resource allocation and an issue of skilling a workforce that is capable of dealing with the infrastructure crisis at present, that is why as the Water Crisis Committee are engaging directly with communities so that we can come to some form of a resolution on how we can move forward."